WEBVTT

00:12.055 --> 00:14.014
I'm retiring.

00:14.057 --> 00:15.363
What?
Why?

00:15.406 --> 00:17.582
I've done as much
as I can do here.

00:17.626 --> 00:19.410
I will stay
until the end of the year,

00:19.454 --> 00:22.196
but after that I should move on.

00:22.239 --> 00:24.285
<i>STR Laurie wants
a 20% downsizing</i>

00:24.328 --> 00:26.069
of the firm.

00:26.113 --> 00:28.550
Okay. I retire.

00:28.593 --> 00:29.464
That'll be cut in half.

00:29.507 --> 00:30.639
Do you believe him?

00:30.682 --> 00:32.728
This is some selfless act?

00:32.771 --> 00:34.469
Are you kidding me?

00:34.512 --> 00:37.646
This is about
the Democratic Party.

00:38.734 --> 00:41.737
Four years from now, we need
an African American candidate

00:41.780 --> 00:43.869
-that can go the distance.
-So, how can I help?

00:43.913 --> 00:46.568
You can be that candidate.

00:47.960 --> 00:49.832
you write a book.

00:49.875 --> 00:52.313
A political statement.

00:52.356 --> 00:53.792
And a memoir.

00:53.836 --> 00:55.707
Got you a contract
with Simon & Schuster

00:55.751 --> 00:58.188
to write about
your political awakening.

01:04.194 --> 01:06.414
Years ago,
I wanted to create

01:06.457 --> 01:08.677
a law firm run entirely
by women,

01:08.720 --> 01:10.722
but it never worked out.

01:10.766 --> 01:12.594
So, why not now?

01:12.637 --> 01:15.336
--What, Reddick/
-Lockhart?
-Just you and me.

01:15.379 --> 01:17.729
-We don't bring in a third.
-Partners?

01:18.730 --> 01:19.862
Partners.

01:19.905 --> 01:22.343
Stella Corben.
I am Inspector General

01:22.386 --> 01:23.692
at the Department of Justice.

01:23.735 --> 01:26.173
I say this with a heavy heart,

01:26.216 --> 01:29.306
but Judge Cain is guilty
of accepting a bribe.

01:29.350 --> 01:32.918
This carries a sentence
of up to 15 years.

01:32.962 --> 01:34.485
Isn't this retribution

01:34.529 --> 01:35.704
for Judge Cain's coming
to your office,

01:35.747 --> 01:37.880
requesting whistleblower
protection?

01:37.923 --> 01:39.447
Of course not.

01:39.490 --> 01:41.449
You're here as a whistleblower,
Julius.

01:41.492 --> 01:43.929
<i>Didn't Judge Cain come
to your office</i>

01:43.973 --> 01:47.411
with accusations about
something called Memo 618?

01:47.455 --> 01:50.327
I have no idea
what you're talking about.

01:50.371 --> 01:52.547
<i>Memo 618 is a document</i>

01:52.590 --> 01:55.376
<i>used to intimidate judges
into ruling</i>

01:55.419 --> 01:56.986
for the more powerful party.

01:57.029 --> 01:59.554
And you are testifying
that Judge Cain

01:59.597 --> 02:01.730
didn't come to your office
regarding this?

02:01.773 --> 02:04.733
I'm testifying that
Judge Cain came to my office

02:04.776 --> 02:08.824
to put pressure on me
to drop the bribery charge.

02:08.867 --> 02:11.783
Well, it's a good thing
I recorded that meeting.

02:12.828 --> 02:14.438
Objection.

02:14.482 --> 02:17.572
Counselor, is that
a one-party consent recording?

02:17.615 --> 02:18.921
It is, but in federal court,

02:18.964 --> 02:20.401
one-party consent
is permissible.

02:20.444 --> 02:22.577
We're in Illinois,
a two-party state.

02:22.620 --> 02:24.231
Sustained.

02:24.274 --> 02:26.320
-They're going to destroy me.
-We'll move for a recusal.

02:26.363 --> 02:28.235
She'll just deny it.

02:28.278 --> 02:29.975
Not if we threaten
to expose her complicity

02:30.019 --> 02:32.761
-regarding Memo 618.
-How can we do that?

02:32.804 --> 02:35.546
♪ <i>The itsy bitsy spider</i>♪

02:35.590 --> 02:38.723
-♪ <i>Crawled up the water spout</i>♪

02:38.767 --> 02:43.337
♪ <i>Down came the rain
and washed the spider out.♪</i>

02:43.380 --> 02:44.425
Who died?

02:45.817 --> 02:48.342
That is the Lucca
I know and love.

02:48.385 --> 02:49.778
Bianca.

02:49.821 --> 02:51.562
Um, what time is it?

02:51.606 --> 02:53.608
12:30. Are you asleep?

02:53.651 --> 02:55.262
-No.

02:55.305 --> 02:57.307
No, no, no.
What do you need?

02:57.351 --> 02:59.831
-What are you doing? <i>
-Bianca, you always ask me that.</i>

02:59.875 --> 03:01.616
My life is not that interesting.

03:01.659 --> 03:03.748
I go to work. I go to bed.

03:03.792 --> 03:05.576
<i>I don't jet off
to exotic places.</i>

03:05.620 --> 03:07.317
I need you to fly to England.

03:07.361 --> 03:10.015
-What? <i>
-I need you to go to England</i>

03:10.059 --> 03:11.930
<i>to buy the St. Lucia resort
for me.</i>

03:11.974 --> 03:13.541
<i>Be my proxy.
Get a good price.</i>

03:13.584 --> 03:16.283
Okay. Uh, when?

03:16.326 --> 03:17.719
Tomorrow. Hold on.

03:18.894 --> 03:20.069
-Mm-hmm. <i>
-Bianca,</i>

03:20.112 --> 03:23.464
I-I've never been
outside of the country.

03:23.507 --> 03:25.074
You went to St. Lucia.

03:25.117 --> 03:26.467
For three hours.

03:26.510 --> 03:28.338
Well, now you're going
for three weeks.

03:28.382 --> 03:29.600
Call me when you get there.

03:29.644 --> 03:30.993
Bianca.

03:31.036 --> 03:32.734
-I have a son. <i>
-I know.</i>

03:32.777 --> 03:34.997
I have a nanny
for you and Joseph on the plane.

03:35.040 --> 03:36.868
Call me when you get there.

03:36.912 --> 03:40.481
♪ <i>The rain
and washed the spider out.♪</i>

03:42.352 --> 03:44.659
So, what I have in mind is
a book called <i>Ten Cases,</i>

03:44.702 --> 03:47.705
outlining my top ten
police brutality cases,

03:47.749 --> 03:51.361
making the connection between
police and systemic racism.

03:51.405 --> 03:52.928
Oh, I love it.

03:52.971 --> 03:55.322
So, how about this?
Talk about your ten cases

03:55.365 --> 03:57.062
but how they opened your mind

03:57.106 --> 03:59.717
about how white and Black
can work together.

03:59.761 --> 04:02.720
But that's not really
the book I want to write.

04:02.764 --> 04:04.853
I understand.
I understand but consider it.

04:04.896 --> 04:07.116
Your Honor,
this is a high-conflict divorce.

04:07.159 --> 04:10.075
And the key is
this psychological study.

04:10.119 --> 04:11.947
I wouldn't present it
as a psychological study.

04:11.990 --> 04:13.340
Just use the evidence.

04:13.383 --> 04:14.950
When I want your legal opinion,
I'll ask for it.

04:14.993 --> 04:17.126
David,
this judge rejects psycholog...

04:17.169 --> 04:20.738
Your Honor, I'd like to submit
as evidence this study

04:20.782 --> 04:23.480
that the respondent has
narcissistic...

04:23.524 --> 04:25.090
Don't bother, Counselor.

04:25.134 --> 04:27.136
Psychiatrists can make
anything sound bad.

04:27.179 --> 04:30.531
Lucca, I have a friend
who's frustrated.

04:30.574 --> 04:31.967
I need some advice for her.

04:32.010 --> 04:33.664
<i>Marissa, where are you?</i>

04:33.708 --> 04:35.449
In court.
Why? Where are you?

04:36.493 --> 04:38.060
In London.

04:38.103 --> 04:39.931
Good, say hi
to the queen for me.

04:39.975 --> 04:43.892
This friend is getting
frustrated with her job,

04:43.935 --> 04:46.111
and she maybe wants to be
a lawyer.

04:46.155 --> 04:47.852
What's the quickest way
she could become one?

04:47.896 --> 04:49.550
<i>-What do you mean, the quickest?
-I don't know, like,</i>

04:49.593 --> 04:51.595
is there some way
to accelerate the process?

04:51.639 --> 04:53.945
Some schools offer
a 3+3 program.

04:53.989 --> 04:55.512
You can go to law school

04:55.556 --> 04:57.079
during your last year
of college.

04:57.122 --> 04:59.386
No, no, she's not in college.
She has a job.

04:59.429 --> 05:00.822
She just...

05:00.865 --> 05:02.519
Okay, it's me.

05:02.563 --> 05:04.042
-You want to become a lawyer? <i>
-I don't know.</i>

05:04.086 --> 05:06.784
I'm just checking.
I hate being talked down to.

05:06.828 --> 05:09.570
Okay. First of all,
you'd be great.

05:09.613 --> 05:11.093
I would, wouldn't I?

05:11.136 --> 05:12.660
-I could wipe the floor
in court. <i>
-Second of all,</i>

05:12.703 --> 05:14.444
enroll at law school.

05:14.488 --> 05:15.576
Take summer programs.

05:15.619 --> 05:16.751
You can get it down
to two years.

05:16.794 --> 05:17.969
-Oy. <i>
-I know.</i>

05:18.013 --> 05:19.754
It's... it's not easy.

05:19.797 --> 05:23.410
-Where are you, in church?

05:23.453 --> 05:25.412
<i>No. That must be Big Ben.</i>

05:25.455 --> 05:27.675
Okay, uh,
let's talk when you get in.

05:27.718 --> 05:30.852
Marissa,
I am actually really in London.

05:30.895 --> 05:32.767
Okay, I'll come by your office
this afternoon.

06:02.710 --> 06:04.712
Jay, hey, uh...

06:04.755 --> 06:06.888
Can I call you back, man?
I'm kind of, kind of busy.

06:06.931 --> 06:09.760
Who-who is this?

06:09.804 --> 06:12.633
It's Adrian, Jay,
you called me.

06:12.676 --> 06:14.504
<i>Why did I call you?</i>

06:14.548 --> 06:15.984
Jay, I'm trying to write
right now.

06:16.027 --> 06:18.813
I... I think...

06:18.856 --> 06:21.119
I think you're my father.

06:21.163 --> 06:23.644
Okay.

06:23.687 --> 06:25.776
All right, get some rest.
We'll talk tomorrow.

06:25.820 --> 06:27.038
All right? <i>
-Something's wrong.</i>

06:27.082 --> 06:29.258
I'm having trouble seeing.

06:33.523 --> 06:34.655
Where are you, Jay?

06:41.531 --> 06:44.012
Jay, listen to me.
Did you take anything?

06:44.055 --> 06:46.057
No. I don't like pills.

06:46.101 --> 06:47.537
Where are we going?

06:47.581 --> 06:48.843
We're going to the hospital.

06:48.886 --> 06:50.279
There's something very wrong
with you.

06:50.322 --> 06:51.846
What?

06:51.889 --> 06:53.282
I-I... I don't know.

06:53.325 --> 06:56.024
There's this thing from China.

06:56.067 --> 06:57.852
Have you been
with anybody from overseas?

06:59.331 --> 07:01.812
I don't know.

07:01.856 --> 07:04.032
-What-What's from China?
-Just stay still.

07:04.075 --> 07:05.512
Don't try to get up.

07:22.920 --> 07:24.966
Hello, Diane.
Thanks for meeting with us.

07:25.009 --> 07:26.228
How could I not?

07:26.271 --> 07:28.578
What can I do for you,
Mr. Bloomberg?

07:28.622 --> 07:29.971
Let me take you back to 2016.

07:30.014 --> 07:31.799
-Pre-Trump?
-No.

07:31.842 --> 07:33.714
Post-Harry Dargis.

07:33.757 --> 07:35.063
Remember that name?

07:35.106 --> 07:36.586
Of course.

07:36.630 --> 07:39.067
Four years ago, I represented
him in federal court.

07:39.110 --> 07:40.590
His daughter was shot
and killed.

07:40.634 --> 07:41.765
With an illegally purchased gun.

07:41.809 --> 07:43.724
-And we lost.
-But we had a good case,

07:43.767 --> 07:45.552
and now we're working
on the appeal.

07:45.595 --> 07:47.815
We have a date in front of the
Supreme Court later this year.

07:47.858 --> 07:49.120
Really?

08:02.786 --> 08:03.918
<i>What were you working on?</i>

08:03.961 --> 08:05.920
-My book.
-Oh, right.

08:05.963 --> 08:07.748
How is that going?

08:07.791 --> 08:09.271
It's bullshit.

08:10.881 --> 08:12.143
What about you?

08:12.187 --> 08:14.885
Oh, it's this Supreme Court
gun control case.

08:14.929 --> 08:17.279
Could be really momentous.

08:17.322 --> 08:18.715
But...?

08:18.759 --> 08:20.282
They have the wrong strategy.

08:20.325 --> 08:23.372
They're making technical points
when they really should be

08:23.415 --> 08:25.809
trying to sway
Chief Justice Roberts.

08:25.853 --> 08:27.419
Okay.

08:28.986 --> 08:30.161
Tell 'em that.

08:30.205 --> 08:32.033
D.C. lawyers.

08:32.076 --> 08:34.035
-They don't want to hear it.

08:38.343 --> 08:39.867
What the fuck?!

08:41.912 --> 08:43.348
-Whoa!
-The fuck?

08:50.094 --> 08:52.314
Can I tell you
what I really want?

08:54.838 --> 08:56.710
Sure. What?

08:56.753 --> 09:00.104
I want to argue
in front of the Supreme Court.

09:02.150 --> 09:04.369
If that's what you want,

09:04.413 --> 09:06.720
you fucking tell 'em that.

09:07.721 --> 09:10.288
I'm telling them
my book is shit.

09:12.464 --> 09:14.075
Tell 'em.

09:21.299 --> 09:23.650
-Bottoms up.

09:25.695 --> 09:27.001
Mr. Bloomberg.

09:27.044 --> 09:29.003
Oh, yes, sorry. Mike.

09:29.046 --> 09:31.005
Yeah, I think we have
a real case here,

09:31.048 --> 09:33.224
and I want to be involved.

09:33.268 --> 09:36.793
But I think it's essential
that I be the mouthpiece

09:36.837 --> 09:38.099
-in front of the Court.

09:38.142 --> 09:40.144
-Hello?
-Well,

09:40.188 --> 09:42.016
I'll tell you, the key is

09:42.059 --> 09:44.279
-to bring Chief Justice Roberts
over to our side.
-Yeah, hold on.

09:44.322 --> 09:46.194
Uh, Adrian's calling.

09:46.237 --> 09:50.372
Uh, no, and I think I have
a John Roberts secret weapon.

09:50.415 --> 09:52.374
-She's gonna have
to call you back.
-I already talked to the client

09:52.417 --> 09:53.941
-and he agrees.

09:54.985 --> 09:56.683
Yes. Great.

09:56.726 --> 09:58.467
So, I-I will call you back.

10:00.512 --> 10:02.079
Good news?

10:02.123 --> 10:03.951
For me.

10:03.994 --> 10:06.780
I am arguing
in front of the Supreme Court.

10:06.823 --> 10:09.043
For you, eh...

10:09.086 --> 10:11.045
I'm getting your beloved guns
off the street.

10:11.088 --> 10:12.786
My beloved guns?

10:12.829 --> 10:14.701
Now I need something from you,
my darling bear.

10:14.744 --> 10:16.224
Oh, God.

10:16.267 --> 10:17.529
What?

10:18.748 --> 10:20.968
Be my John Roberts.

10:23.535 --> 10:25.059
Hey, Julius.

10:25.102 --> 10:26.147
-How is he?
-They just closed the doors.

10:26.190 --> 10:27.757
They're not letting anybody in.

10:27.801 --> 10:29.106
-Why not?
-It's this coronavirus thing.

10:29.150 --> 10:30.934
They're afraid it's spreading.

10:31.979 --> 10:33.850
-Where are you going?
-To see him.

10:33.894 --> 10:35.983
-The doctors said no.
-Well, then they can stop me.

10:52.956 --> 10:56.786
<i>They've come back to me with
one inescapable conclusion.</i>

10:56.830 --> 11:00.181
To avoid the loss of potentially
tens of thousands of lives,

11:00.224 --> 11:03.488
we must enact an immediate
stay-at-home order

11:03.532 --> 11:05.316
<i>for the state of Illinois.</i>

11:05.360 --> 11:08.406
<i>So that is the action
that I'm announcing today.</i>

11:08.450 --> 11:12.062
<i>We have looked closely
at the trajectory of this virus</i>

11:12.106 --> 11:14.325
<i>in countries
like Italy and China.</i>

11:14.369 --> 11:17.546
<i>Left unchecked, cases
in Illinois will rise rapidly.</i>

11:17.589 --> 11:19.156
<i>All we know</i>

11:19.200 --> 11:21.463
is that this
stay-at-home order will last

11:21.506 --> 11:23.378
until April 8th.

11:23.421 --> 11:25.293
At that point, you'll all
be getting invitations

11:25.336 --> 11:26.773
-to come back to work.
-Are we all being asked back?

11:26.816 --> 11:28.165
We hope so,

11:28.209 --> 11:29.950
-but we really don't know.
-How do we know

11:29.993 --> 11:31.299
-whether we still have a job?
-We'll be calling you guys

11:31.342 --> 11:32.822
hopefully within a week.

11:32.866 --> 11:33.954
So we just wait by the phone?

11:33.997 --> 11:35.085
In the meantime,
we're setting up

11:35.129 --> 11:37.305
a teleconferencing
infrastructure.

11:37.348 --> 11:41.788
So download a program
called Zoom.com.

11:41.831 --> 11:44.791
Z-O-O-M.

11:44.834 --> 11:46.401
Get on your computers.

11:46.444 --> 11:48.838
Zoom.com.

11:48.882 --> 11:51.188
I hate saying this, but...

11:51.232 --> 11:53.147
Yeah.
I'm thinking the same thing.

11:53.190 --> 11:57.325
It's a better opportunity for
us to start laying off our 20%.

11:58.413 --> 12:00.502
-Are you kidding me? <i>
-You weren't at the office,</i>

12:00.545 --> 12:03.505
so I just wanted to be
the one who told you.

12:03.548 --> 12:04.985
So you're firing me?

12:05.028 --> 12:07.161
<i>No, but given this pandemic,</i>

12:07.204 --> 12:09.946
<i>there's just no practical work
for an investigator.</i>

12:09.990 --> 12:12.166
I'm sorry, Marissa.

12:12.209 --> 12:13.515
I'm sorry, too.

12:21.044 --> 12:23.003
Okay, I'm going to law school.
Where should I go?

12:23.046 --> 12:25.092
Let me think about it, Marissa.

12:25.135 --> 12:26.615
I'll call you back.

12:28.617 --> 12:30.010
Okay.

12:30.053 --> 12:31.881
So...

12:31.925 --> 12:34.492
let's take a break.

12:35.537 --> 12:37.408
How are the negotiations going?

12:37.452 --> 12:39.062
<i>We're still ten million off.</i>

12:39.106 --> 12:40.542
<i>That's good enough.</i>

12:40.585 --> 12:42.196
<i>You can say yes if you want.</i>

12:42.239 --> 12:45.112
Why am I more concerned
about your money than you are?

12:45.155 --> 12:46.940
'Cause you're good at your job.

12:46.983 --> 12:48.855
-Now, what'd you need? <i>
-Actually, it's not for me.</i>

12:48.898 --> 12:50.030
<i>It's for a friend.</i>

12:50.073 --> 12:51.422
She wants to go to law school,

12:51.466 --> 12:53.860
and I know you gave
an endowment to Chicago-Kent

12:53.903 --> 12:55.339
because I approved it.

12:55.383 --> 12:57.080
So I was hoping
you can make a call.

12:57.124 --> 12:59.604
You call. You represent me.

12:59.648 --> 13:02.346
They're not gonna take
a call from Lucca Quinn.

13:02.390 --> 13:04.566
<i>They will
because they know you're me.</i>

13:04.609 --> 13:07.221
Now I have a proposal for you.

13:07.264 --> 13:08.700
Okay.

13:38.382 --> 13:40.428
-Hello? <i>
Hello?</i>

13:40.471 --> 13:42.343
<i>I was given this number
for Marissa Gold.</i>

13:42.386 --> 13:44.606
This is she,
but I don't work here anymore.

13:44.649 --> 13:46.913
<i>Ms. Gold,
my name is Rasputin Loggins,</i>

13:46.956 --> 13:48.610
<i>and I work
for the admittance office</i>

13:48.653 --> 13:50.612
<i>of the Chicago-Kent
College of Law.</i>

13:50.655 --> 13:53.441
<i>And we want to congratulate you
for joining</i>

13:53.484 --> 13:55.095
<i>our first-year program.</i>

13:55.138 --> 13:56.531
What?

13:57.532 --> 14:00.187
<i>Welcome to the world of law.</i>

14:00.230 --> 14:02.929
Are you sure
you want to do this?

14:02.972 --> 14:05.627
We're sheltering-in-place.

14:05.670 --> 14:08.369
Why not together?

14:08.412 --> 14:10.414
Mm.

14:12.199 --> 14:14.636
You could end up hating me.

14:14.679 --> 14:17.552
It's a risk.

14:17.595 --> 14:20.468
-Or I could end up hating you.
-Mm-mm.

14:20.511 --> 14:22.296
No way in the world.

14:22.339 --> 14:24.472
I'm way too lovable.

14:28.519 --> 14:29.956
<i>Breaking news.</i>

14:29.999 --> 14:32.132
<i>We're getting eyewitness
footage out of Minnesota</i>

14:32.175 --> 14:33.611
<i>of a deadly police encounter.</i>

14:33.655 --> 14:35.048
<i>A warning to our viewers,</i>

14:35.091 --> 14:37.093
<i>this video contains
graphic violence.</i>

14:37.137 --> 14:39.530
<i>A 46-year-old Black man
was stopped</i>

14:39.574 --> 14:42.664
<i>for allegedly buying cigarettes
with a counterfeit $20 bill.</i>

